4)

set.seed(1)
x = rnorm(100, 0, 1)
random = rnorm(100, 0, 1)
y = ifelse(random > 0, - 2 * x ^ 2 + 3 * x + 2, - 2 * x ^ 2 + 3 * x)
data2 = as.data.frame(cbind(y, x))
data2$class = ifelse(random <= 0, 1, 0)
data2$class = as.factor(data2$class)
plot(y ~ x, data2, col = ifelse(data2$class == 1, "red", "darkblue"), main = "Simulated data", xlab = "", ylab = "")

train = data2[1:75,]
test = data2[76:100,]
T.Error = function(model, data, type){
  ypred = predict(model, data)
  if (type == "train") {
    print(table(predict = ypred, type = data$class))
    print("Training Error:")
    return(1 - (table(ypred, data$class)[1,1] + table(ypred, data$class)[2,2])/nrow(data))
  } else if (type == "test") {
    print(table(predict = ypred, type = data$class))
    print("Test Error:")
    return(1 - (table(ypred, data$class)[1,1] + table(ypred, data$class)[2,2])/nrow(data))
  }
}
linearfit1 = svm(class ~ ., data = train, kernel = "linear", cost = 5)
plot(linearfit1, train)

# Model Fit.
T.Error(linearfit1, train, "train")
##        type
## predict  0  1
##       0 20  0
##       1  8 47
## [1] "Training Error:"
## [1] 0.1066667
T.Error(linearfit1, test, "test")
##        type
## predict  0  1
##       0  8  0
##       1  4 13
## [1] "Test Error:"
## [1] 0.16
radial = svm(class ~ ., data = train, kernel = "radial", cost = 5, gamma = 1)
plot(radial, train)

# Model Fit
T.Error(radial, train, "train")
##        type
## predict  0  1
##       0 27  0
##       1  1 47
## [1] "Training Error:"
## [1] 0.01333333
T.Error(radial, test, "test")
##        type
## predict  0  1
##       0 11  0
##       1  1 13
## [1] "Test Error:"
## [1] 0.04
polynomial = svm(class ~ ., data = train, kernel = "polynomial", cost = 5, degree = 2)
plot(polynomial, train)

# Model Fit
T.Error(polynomial, train, "train")
##        type
## predict  0  1
##       0  2  1
##       1 26 46
## [1] "Training Error:"
## [1] 0.36
T.Error(polynomial, test, "test")
##        type
## predict  0  1
##       0  0  0
##       1 12 13
## [1] "Test Error:"
## [1] 0.48

The results show that the radial model is the one with the best fit to the data. It misclassified only one observation in the training and in the test data. It has a Training Error of \(0.013\) and a Test Error of \(0.04\).

c)

set.seed(1)
train = sample(1000, 800)
test = data6[-train,]
train = data6[train,]
costs = c(10^-3, 10^-2, 10^-1, 10^0, 5, 10^1, 10^2)
train.errors = c()
test.errors = c()
for(i in 1:length(costs)){
  model = svm(as.factor(y) ~ ., train, kernel = "linear", cost = costs[i])
  pred = predict(model, train, type = "response")
  train.errors = c(train.errors, 1 - (table(pred, train$y)[1,1] + table(pred, train$y)[2,2])/nrow(train))
  pred = predict(model, test, type = "response")
  test.errors = c(test.errors, 1 - (table(pred, test$y)[1,1] + table(pred, test$y)[2,2])/nrow(test))
}
data.frame(cost = costs, train.errors, test.errors, train.missclass = train.errors * nrow(train), test.missclass = test.errors * nrow(test))
##    cost train.errors test.errors train.missclass test.missclass
## 1 1e-03      0.00250       0.015               2              3
## 2 1e-02      0.01500       0.020              12              4
## 3 1e-01      0.00750       0.010               6              2
## 4 1e+00      0.00125       0.000               1              0
## 5 5e+00      0.00250       0.000               2              0
## 6 1e+01      0.00125       0.005               1              1
## 7 1e+02      0.00250       0.015               2              3

Comparing the test error of models with different costs we see that the model with the lowest test error is the one with a cost equal to \(1\) (it has no missclassification), it also presents one of the lowest training errors (it misclassifies 1 observations in the training data set). Comparing it to the Cross Validation results we see that the CV approach would end up recommending us to use a cost equal to \(10\).

d) We see that there is no rule of thumb to find the best cost. It can lies on bigger or smaller values depending on the problem we are trying to solve.

Comparing the best radial model with the best polynomial model we can see that they present very similar performances. The best radial model with \(gamma = 0.5\) and \(cost = 10\) missclassifies 15 observations. Meanwhile the polynomial model of \(degree = 3\) and \(cost = 10\) missclassifies 31 observations. T.Error = function(model, data, type){
  ypred = predict(model, data, type = "response")
  if (type == "train") {
    print(table(predict = ypred, type = data$Purchase))
    print("Training Error:")
    return(1 - (table(ypred, data$Purchase)[1,1] + table(ypred, data$Purchase)[2,2])/nrow(data))
  } else if (type == "test") {
    print(table(predict = ypred, type = data$Purchase))
    print("Test Error:")
    return(1 - (table(ypred, data$Purchase)[1,1] + table(ypred, data$Purchase)[2,2])/nrow(data))
  }
}
